ch <i>abt</i> ‘abbot’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a servant of an abbot or a nickname for someone thought to resemble an abbot in some way. In some instances it may have been a topographic or habitational name referring to a house named with this word.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): variant of   Abt  , a habitational name from Opatów in Poland."]},{"name":"Apter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Avrohom, Bronya, Eliezer, Naftali.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Apt (see   Apt  ).","English: habitational name from Aptor in Marldon, Devon, composed of Old English <i>uppe</i> ‘up, above’ + <i>torr</i> ‘rocky outcrop’."]}]},{"name":"Madog","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French Canadian: variant of   Madore  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Madore","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Eusebe, Fernand, Lucien, Normand, Adhemar, Adrien, Donat, Elzear, Francois, Gaetan, Gilles.","French Canadian: from a French shortened form of the Spanish personal name <i>Amador</i>, from Latin <i>Amator</i> (from <i>amator</i> ‘lover’), a Christian saint's name. Compare   Mador  .","In some cases possibly also Breton (<b>Madoré</b>): nickname meaning literally ‘good help’, from Old Breton <i>mat</i> ‘good’ and <i>uuoret</i> ‘help’."]}]},{"name":"Gruffudd","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."],"variants":[{"name":"Griffudd","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."]},{"name":"Gruffud","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."]},{"name":"Griffith","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Gruffudd ."]}]},{"name":"Goch","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Italian <b>Rocco</b>; ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Gruffudd Goch ap Madog was born about 1374, in Bangor, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 daughters with Gruffudd Goch ap Madog."},"et":{"about 1374–":"umbes 1374–Surnud","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1396–Female":"1396–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1374–Female":"1374–Surnud","1374":"1374","1396":"1396","about 1374":"umbes 1374","about 1396":"umbes 1396","1370":"1370","Bangor, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Bangor, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of Bangor Fawr,Is Gwyrfai,Caernarvonshire,Wales":"Bangor, Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1374–":"noin 1374–Kuollut","1370–Male":"1370–Kuollut","1396–Female":"1396–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1374–Female":"1374–Kuollut","1374":"1374","1396":"1396","about 1374":"noin 1374","about 1396":"noin 1396","1370":"1370","Bangor, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Bangor, Carmarthenshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","of Bangor Fawr,Is Gwyrfai,Caernarvonshire,Wales":"Bangor, Caernarfonshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1374–":"environ 1374–Décédée","1370–Male":"1370–Décédé","1396–Female":"1396–Décédée","–Female":"Décédée","1374–Female":"1374–Déc